Oracle SOA interview Questions and Answers:
Oracle SOA ‚Äì Question 1
In an Oracle SOA composite, what is the role of a Mediator, and how is it different from a BPEL process?
BPEL Process
‚Ä¢	Designed for stateful, long-running orchestration
‚Ä¢	Supports:
o	Parallel & sequential flows
o	Compensation & fault handling
o	Complex business logic
‚Ä¢	Best choice when:
o	You need process flow control
o	You need to maintain state
o	You have human tasks, timers, or wait activities
Mediator
‚Ä¢	Designed for stateless, lightweight mediation
‚Ä¢	Mainly used for:
o	Routing
o	Filtering
o	Simple XSLT transformations
o	Event handling (EDN)
‚Ä¢	Best choice when:
o	You need fast, synchronous message handling
o	You don‚Äôt need to maintain state
________________________________________
‚≠ê One-line interview comparison (very powerful)
BPEL is for complex, stateful orchestration, while Mediator is for lightweight, stateless routing and transformation.

Oracle SOA ‚Äì Question 2
What is the difference between an abstract WSDL and a concrete WSDL?
Abstract WSDL defines the service contract ‚Äî what operations exist and what messages are exchanged ‚Äî while Concrete WSDL defines the implementation details such as protocol, binding, and endpoint location.
If you want to sound extra strong, add this one line:
Abstract WSDL is protocol-independent, while Concrete WSDL is protocol-specific.

Oracle SOA ‚Äì Question 3 (Surprise)
In Oracle SOA, what is the difference between a business fault and a system fault?
üëâ Explain:
‚Ä¢	What causes each
‚Ä¢	How they are typically handled
Key refinements (important for Oracle SOA interviews)
Business Fault
‚Ä¢	Expected fault
‚Ä¢	Explicitly modeled in the WSDL
‚Ä¢	Thrown deliberately using fault activity in BPEL
‚Ä¢	Used when:
o	Input is valid XML
o	Business rule fails
Examples:
‚Ä¢	Insufficient balance
‚Ä¢	Salary exceeds limit
‚Ä¢	Invalid order quantity
üëâ Keyword: expected / modeled / functional
________________________________________
System Fault
‚Ä¢	Unexpected fault
‚Ä¢	Caused by infrastructure or runtime issues
‚Ä¢	Not defined by business
‚Ä¢	Happens automatically
Examples:
‚Ä¢	Adapter unavailable
‚Ä¢	Database down
‚Ä¢	Timeout
‚Ä¢	SOAP fault due to system error
üëâ Keyword: unexpected / technical / runtime
________________________________________
‚≠ê Best 2-line interview answer (memorize this)
Business faults are expected, business-defined errors explicitly modeled in the WSDL and thrown intentionally, whereas system faults are unexpected technical errors caused by infrastructure or runtime failures.
________________________________________
üí° Extra SOA-specific point (bonus)
‚Ä¢	Business faults ‚Üí usually caught using specific fault handlers
‚Ä¢	System faults ‚Üí often caught using catch-all (catchAll) fault handlers

